The High court has awarded Dennis Itumbi Sh5 million for illegal detention and arrest over alleged hacking of the ICC website in 2012. The State House senior director of digital communications sued the government after he was arrested and detained without trial. The ruling was delivered by Justice Joseph Onguto of the Constitutional and Human Rights Division on Tuesday. Itumbi had sought Sh50 million as compensation in the case. Read: Itumbi sues state over 2012 arrest Attorney General Githu Muigai, Director of Public Prosecutions Keriako Tobiko and Police Inspector General Joseph Boinett were the respondents. In his suit paper, Itumbi claimed his arrest was influenced by his close relations with President Uhuru Kenyatta. Uhuru was at that time facing charges of crimes against humanity at the ICC. Itumbi was arrested in Embu and detained in different police stations for close to four days. This was after former ICC Prosecutor Luis Moreno-Ocampo claimed that his e-mail account was hacked. The prosecutor alleged that key witnesses against Uhuru and DP William Ruto were threatened. Read: Itumbi charged with hacking computer data Click here for the latest political news  